## PR Type
Feature / Refactoring


## PR Checklist
- [x] Tests for the changes have been added / updated.
- [x] Documentation comments have been added / updated.
- [x] A changelog entry has been made for the appropriate packages.
- [x] Format code with the latest stable rustfmt.


## Overview
In order to support long-lived sessions with auto-refresh, we need to introduce a new concept into `actix-session`: `TtlExtensionPolicy`.  
This cannot be done in a backwards-compatible fashion because `SessionLength` exposes its fields directly therefore adding new fields to its variants it's a breaking change.

This PR does the following:

- Rename `SessionLength::Predetermined` to `SessionLength::PersistentSession`;
- Refactor `SessionLength` to make it possible to evolve configuration options for its variants, in the future, in a backwards-compatible fashion. Each variant became its own type (`BrowserSession`, `PersistentSession`) and their fields are exposed via builder methods, not directly;
- Rename `SessionLength` to `SessionLifecycle` to use a terminology that is less ambiguous now that we allow the extension of the session length at various points of the session lifecycle;
- Rename `max_session_length` to `session_ttl` in `PersistentSession`;
- Rename `state_ttl` to `session_state_ttl` in `BrowserSession`;
- Add `TtlExtensionPolicy` and a corresponding method on `PersistentSession` and `BrowserSession`. `TtlExtensionPolicy` is marked as `non_exhaustive` to give us the possibility to introduce different strategies in the future without making a breaking change (e.g. refresh the TTL at most once every X minutes);
- Add a new `update_ttl` method to `SessionStore`. This opens up the door to an optimised implementation, depending on the backend, compared to invoking `SessionStore::update` when we simply want to extend the state TTL;
- Move all types related to the configuration of `SessionMiddleware` into a public `configuration` sub-module. This results into a clean homepage for docs, highlighting the types we want users to focus on (`SessionMiddleware`, `Session`).

The default behaviour remains unchanged - we refresh the TTL exclusively on session state changes.

Closes #231.
